@RalfJung "No-cross-allocation offsets" *is* spatial but doesn't *actually* need to know about the allocations in play. All you need to know is that you have a pointer bounded to some slice of memory and `offset`ing or read/writing beyond it is UB.

Not being able to merge slices is, as far as I know, wholy covered by "provenance only gets smaller, not bigger". One of the two pointers would be "derived" into a larger provenance, which isn't allowed.

I think appealing to actual allocations is only needed for freeing and expiring borrows.

